refsect2.para:
When you add a widget to its parent container, the parent container will do this:
g_object_ref_sink (G_OBJECT (child_widget));
This means that the container now owns a reference to the child widget and the child widget has no floating reference.

The purpose of the floating reference is to keep the child widget alive
until you add it to a parent container:

   button = gtk_button_new ();
   /* button has one floating reference to keep it alive */
   gtk_container_add (GTK_CONTAINER (container), button);
   /* button has one non-floating reference owned by the container */

refsect2.programlisting:
typedef enum
{
  GTK_IN_DESTRUCTION	= 1 << 0, /* Used internally during dispose */
#if !defined (GTK_DISABLE_DEPRECATED) || defined (GTK_COMPILATION)
  GTK_FLOATING		= 1 << 1,
#endif
  GTK_RESERVED_1	= 1 << 2,
  GTK_RESERVED_2	= 1 << 3
} GtkObjectFlags;

typedef enum
{
  GTK_ARG_READABLE	 = G_PARAM_READABLE,
  GTK_ARG_WRITABLE	 = G_PARAM_WRITABLE,
  GTK_ARG_CONSTRUCT	 = G_PARAM_CONSTRUCT,
  GTK_ARG_CONSTRUCT_ONLY = G_PARAM_CONSTRUCT_ONLY,
  GTK_ARG_CHILD_ARG	 = 1 << 4
} GtkArgFlags;

refsect2.para:
Removes the floating reference from a GtkObject, if it exists;
otherwise does nothing. See the GtkObject overview documentation at
the top of the page.

